social_posts.post_text:
I made a mini for my friend Cindy @liveacolorfullife out of scraps from her pineapple blocks. Sewing with someone else’s scraps really gives you an insight into their fabric taste. I loved playing with these bright and bold colors. I was going to make it a little bigger, but I was limited by the size of the backing. It was a perfect pairing, I think! It measures about 9” square. ❤️

#scrapsaremyfavorite

I started my new Christmas quilt! I am making 12” sawtooth stars, inspired by a the beautiful blanket by @greenletterday and @insidethepaperbox 

I love the colors and was happy to be able to pull all the fabrics from my stash and scrap bins. (Yes, I was surprised....) I’m excited to see how this progresses! Background fabric is Quilter’s Linen in Ecru by Robert Kaufman. 

#stopstashingstartsewing

I made another #finchbucket for a friend’s birthday. ❤️ (wonderful pattern by @stitchmischief ) This is the midi size. I added a leather handle under the casing instead of in the side seam. 

Swipe to see the card that I made using the smallest of my fabric scraps. 💕 I think it turned out pretty cute! I used double sided fusible web (Steam-A-Seam Lite 2) to attach the scraps to the card stock.

I finished this quilt a few weeks ago...the beautiful snowfall this morning proved to be a good motivator to take some pics! 

The background color reads peach in the photos, but it’s actually a really pretty pink. It’s Moda Bella solid in Pale Pink, purchased @stitchsupplyco 

Pattern is based off my scrap happy rails quilt (in my book no scrap left behind) but I changed up the block arrangement. This version uses just under 2 yards of background fabric. The quilt measures 60” x 76”. 

💕💕💕

#stopstashingstartsewing

#pincushionsaremyfavorite

I’ve got a Christmas quilt top! ❤️🌲 

Inspired by the beautiful afghan (second pic) by @greenletterday and @insidethepaperbox 

12” sawtooth stars were made from solids from my stash and scraps. Background is Quilter’s Linen in Ecru. 

Quilt top measures 60” x 72” (or so). 

I do not enjoy making sawtooth stars, but I sure do love the look of them! 

Kona colors used: pink flamingo, punch, watermelon, cardinal, red, limelight, pea pod and grass green. 

Other colors used: lily pad (Cotton Couture), an unknown light aqua (soho solids) and an unknown dark green linen. 

I think this will become a favorite! 

#stopstashingstartsewing

My Wensleydale quilt has been done for a few weeks. My daughter helped me take pics today. 👏🏻 

Excellent pattern by @jenkingwell in her book Quilt Recipes. I made 12 extra blocks to make a twin size quilt. I foundation paper pieced it. 

All fabrics from scraps and stash. 👏🏻 
Backing and binding is from my Emma and Myrtle collection. 

This was my first time doing big stitch binding and I liked it a lot except it was very rough on my hands. (Ouch.) 

Quilting was done by Janet Peterson of Cornerstone Quilting. She did an AMAZING job and was a pleasure to work with! Would definitely recommend. 

I used tips from Debbie Jeske @aquilterstable for quilt holding...temporary corner pockets and telescoping handles (used for painting)....total game changer. 🎉

#stopstashingstartsewing
basting day 🤍

Over the past few weeks I’ve been working on a scrappy trip using the hints and expanded block size by @woodberry_way and the tutorial by @quiltville_bonnie 

I figured it was a good way to use some stash that I’ve been sitting on for way too long. Majority of fabrics by Brenda @pinkcastlefabrics with some others to round things out. 

It’s interesting to see what fabrics get culled from the original pull and what gets added along the way. Still plenty of editing ahead, but that’s what makes it fun. 

Planning a total of 20 blocks for a quilt that measures 64” x 80”. Each square finishes at 2”. My favorite size! ❤️

#stopstashingstartsewing

basting day 💕 

hoping to eek out a Feb finish 🤞🏻

My Christmas stars quilt is done! In all honesty, I thought yesterday was the last day of the month for a few hours, so I found myself with an “extra” day to finish. She is far from perfect, but she’s done. 🎉 

12” sawtooth stars were made from solids. The background is RK ecru colored quilter’s linen. 

Inspiration was a crocheted blanket from @greenletterday 

Backing is a lovely @dsquilts print that I purchased @stitchsupplyco 

I matched the plaid repeat using a glue basting technique. It’s a nerdy thing to do, but once I started a few years ago, I just can’t stop. It’s a little extra work, but the magic of it never gets old. ✨

This is my second quilt finish for the year. 

#stopstashingstartsewing

I finished my scrappy trip quilt top! It’s a big lap size, measuring 64” x 80”. Each square finishes at 2”. It used a LOT of thread. 🧵🧵🧵

I used the scrappy trip tutorial by @quiltville_bonnie and the expanded block size and tips by @woodberry_way 

It was a fun one to make! 

#stopstashingstartsewing

I finished my churn dash quilt top! Honestly, I did not know if I would ever see this one through. I love/hate how stubborn I can be when it comes to finishing. 🙃

I was delighted (!!!!) when I realized I needed 63 rather than 80 blocks to make a decent size lap quilt. 🎉

There is a tutorial on the old blog for this (search scrappy churn dash block tutorial) from 5 years ago, if you would be crazy enough to want to attempt something like this. 

One thing I really love about this quilt (other than the fact that the top is finally done) is the secondary pattern that emerges. ❤️ 

Each block finishes at about 8.5” 
Quilt measures about 59.5”4 x 76.5”
basting today 💕

basting day 💕

second pic...what happens when you are basting and your pieced batting isn’t quite large enough? Take a rug, fold it in half to protect the wood floor and carefully scoot it under the quilt in order to splice in a few more inches of batting. Prevents having to re-tape and reposition the entire quilt/backing/batting. Phew! Also, one could measure more accurately and a avoid this hack all together. 😬

I cut strips of leftover Pellon SF 101 fusible interfacing to join the pieces of batting. It works like a charm and no waste. 👏🏻

I finished knitting my second sweater!!! Pattern is the #flaxlightsweater by @tincanknits 

Many thanks to Maria @quiltmomoffive for generously gifting me the yarn! 🧶 

I’m super happy with the fit. I knit a size large and needed no mods. 🙌🏻
basting day 💕

One of my cousins had a baby girl after having two boys, so she got a very pink quilt. Loved making and giving this quilt! 💕 swipe through to see the adorable recipient. 

#stopstashingstartsewing

Gardening season is in full swing here in MN 🎉 and I have the sore body to prove it. 😂 I grew baby Choi for the first time this year and harvested my first bit of it today. I used it in a stir fry, which also featured chives and cilantro from the garden. I’m so grateful for home grown produce! (And also grateful for egg rolls. 😂)

This is my 9th quilt (out of 10) in my #asalutetosolids personal challenge. I finished this one back in January. (!!!) 

The top is 100% scraps and took forever to piece. It is based on the Missing U pattern in Sunday Morning Quilts. I quilted it on my baby lock Tiara and it’s backed with chambray. 

This quilt has grown on me a lot since I finished it. I’m not complaining. 🤍

It measures 53” x 66”.

I have a goal to finish one quilt a month this year (except during gardening season) and this was my finish for March. 

It’s a scrappy churn dash that took me about 5 years to complete. I love the secondary pattern that emerges by smashing the blocks all together. (Construction was a pain, let me tell ya’, because few of the seams nested. 🙄) Each of the scrappy strips finish about 1” x 4.5”. 

I had 7 tiny churn dashes that I was going to incorporate into the top, but I wasn’t loving any of the arrangements I tried and I did NOT want to make more, so I put them on the back. I think it was meant to be! I love the back so much. 

I finished it off with bias gingham binding. Perfect finishing touch!

The quilt measures about 60” x 76”.

There is a block tutorial for this on the old blog...search “scrappy churn dash” and you should find it. In fact, I think I have a tutorial for the smaller size as well, should you have the gumption to attempt that one. Haha

Anyway, I’m pretty happy with this one...I think I’ll add it to my permanent collection. 🤍

Working on my “hold the mustard” quilt and finally getting the upper hand on this project. Also, improv is hard sometimes. You have to be in the right mindset. At least that’s been my experience. 

#scrapsaremyfavorite 🤍🖤

Totally smitten with this adorable pillow!!! It’s an early birthday gift from my sweet friend @maryonlakepulaski 
Thank you, Mary! ❤️ 

No one (besides me) gets to touch it. 😂

So happy to have a new pillow for my collection! You can’t have too many pillows. (A sentiment my husband is not aligned with. 😂)
Yesterday’s garden harvest. This represents countless (!!!) hours of watering. So grateful for an abundant harvest despite the drought. 🥕🥒🥬
It’s hard to believe that we are celebrating 26 years of marriage today! 🎉 So thankful to have a wonderful guy to walk through life with. ❤️❤️

I only need one more orange block to complete this quilt top. Oh, and a few hundred setting blocks. 😂 Excited about the progress all the same! #focusquilt

My nephew moved to college today, so I made him a big pillow for his dorm. 💚💙 I hand delivered it this morning, because procrastination is a real thing and deadlines help. 

I made my own pillow form (36” square) and then made a quilted pillow cover for it, so it can be removed and washed, if he would ever feel the need. 😂 

Patchwork squares finish at 2”, my absolute favorite size. 

#scrapsaremyfavorite 
#stopstashingstartsewing

If I could only make one quilt pattern for the rest of my life, I would choose log cabin, hands down. 🤍 

I started this quilt a few weeks ago and as I was working on it again today, I found the rhythm of sewing scraps together comforting. There has been so much change in my world lately and way too much busyness. Coming back to this familiar block and taking a break to sew for fun was like a breath of fresh air. So grateful for the ability to make pretty things. It truly is a gift. 💛

#scrapsaremyfavorite

still building my log cabins 💕

I’m happy to have a few of each value completed and feeling like I found my stride in this quilt. The mess gets bigger and bigger with each block, but that’s part of the process.

If you know me at all, you know that I am a big proponent of sorting your scraps by color. However, I’m trying something different for this quilt. I dumped a lot of my scraps into an old metal washtub and I’m letting them mingle. I think it’s going to help me randomize as I build my blocks. So far, so good! 

#scrapsaremyfavorite

I made my first #starhollowquilt block this morning. ❤️ tutorial is by the lovely and talented Jolene of @blueelephantstitches 

I used 2” squares to start with because smaller=cuter. I figured it was a good way to use some squares I previously cut out, but rarely use. This block is 5” unfinished. 

If you know me at all, you KNOW that I always have pincushions on the brain. So....I used 1.5” squares for my next block. I used leftover binding triangles for the star points (extra points for that!) and made this little cutie. I’m squealing over here!!! Loving the dainty floral and the fall vibes. 🧡🍁

Thanks, Jolene, for a fun block tutorial! 

#scrapsaremyfavorite 
#thepincushionproject

basting day 💛

My oldest is engaged! Couldn’t be happier for these two! ❤️❤️

I finished a quilt!!! I’m calling it “bright future.” 

I started making this during the summer at retreat and finished it a few days ago. Somewhere along the way, my daughter decided that she wants it for her going-to-college quilt for next fall. 💛🤍💛🤍 Not sure how my baby is nearly ready for college 😭 but that’s another story. 

Finished size: 66” x 88”
Block size: 6” finished
Quilting: crosshatch done on my Juki. 
All fabrics from my stash! Backing is a bedsheets print from my (old) fabric line Emma & Myrtle. Love that it backs this special quilt for her. 🤍💛 

This quilt is one of my favorites that I’ve ever made in my 23 years of quilting, so it’s fitting that it’s going to my baby girl. 🤍💛

Many thanks to @baker_brianne for the assist in the photo shoot and for choosing a fantastic location. 🤍

It’s not easy to get a glamorous pic of these blocks, so we are going with a real life photo instead. 🤷🏻‍♀️ after years (and years!) of hoarding, my most precious Denyse scraps are finally getting cut up and I’m ACTUALLY using them. Golly. Wonders never cease. 

The block is from the Minneapolis MQG adventure quilt from 2020. This was January’s block (minus the outside borders), which I loved so much that I took a “detour” and decided to make a whole quilt from this single block. There are so many opportunities to play with color, value and print….I’m having a blast! I’m also making a terrific mess, but that comes with the territory. 

Blocks will finish at 9”.

I finished and gifted this quilt earlier this year and I have no idea why I haven’t posted it until now. 🤷🏻‍♀️ 

It’s a scrappy trip based on the clever tutorial by @quiltville_bonnie and the expanded block size by @woodberry_way (I would highly recommend because of the pressing directions, resulting in easily nested seams…essential for an enjoyable quilt making experience!) 

All the fabric came from my stash, backing included. It measures 64” x 80” and I gave it to my future daughter-in-law. 👏🏻

#stopstashingstartsewing

I made this little bag for a friend and I filled it up with goodies for her birthday. 🎉 I used 2” squares (finished) for the outside of the bag and quilted the patchwork panels to flannel to give it some structure, but the bag still cinches up nicely. I used the drawstring bag pattern by @sotakhandmade (it’s a good one!)

One of the gifts I put inside is a patchwork dish towel that coordinates with the bag. (I have a tutorial for that on the old blog.) 

They were fun to make and even more fun to gift! 👏🏻

#scrapsaremyfavorite

It’s fun to pull out seasonal stuff from years ago. This is another tutorial from the old blog. (Search snowflake block tutorial.) I think I like this pillow now more than when I made it. I’m still dreaming of making this design into a whole quilt someday! ❄️🤍 (…and let’s be honest, in a few different color ways. 😆)

it’s fun to pull out newer seasonal stuff, too! I finished this quilt at the end of February…and this is the current view when you walk in my front door. I love the graphic simplicity of this quilt, which was inspired by a gorgeous crochet blanket by @greenletterday 

The blocks are 12” finished sawtooth stars. Background fabric is Ecru quilters linen, which isn’t linen at all; it’s quilting cotton with a subtle linen print on it, making it easier to use than linen. 

I’m loving this new addition to my Christmas quilt collection. 👏🏻

Inspired by my friend @jenib320 and her adorable tea advent calendar, I made a cutie pie little drawstring bag with some quilt back leftovers. I finished this bag and promptly cut out 4 more nearly identical to this one. So that’s my friendly little warning…if you start, I bet you can’t make just one! I skipped the gusset on the bottom, which makes it quicker and easier. 👏🏻 

Lined drawstring bag pattern is by @jenib320 and she also has an expansion pack to go along with it to give you even more options. Endless possibilities! 👏🏻

Fabric is Ruby by Bonnie and Camille and Five & Dime by Heidi Staples.

One of the few presents I made for Christmas this year: a little patchwork throw pillow for my dear friend, Nancy. ❤️ 

Pillow is appropriately 15” square. The triangles finish at about 1 1/2”. (No pattern was used, I made it up as I went.) This is my 4th joy pillow I’ve made over the years and probably my favorite one yet. 👏🏻

Scraps are my favorite. Co-author of Sunday Morning Quilts and Author of No Scrap Left Behind. Mom of 3 humans and 2 dogs. 🐶 🐕 
Colossians 3:23
